This paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) category as it deals with the reliability of Sp02 sensing from wrist-worn devices, which are commonly used for health monitoring. Additionally, the paper discusses the design of an alternative approach for reliable Sp02 sensing, which involves pruning data, indicating a focus on the design of user interfaces and interaction techniques. 

The paper also falls under the Bioinformatics (cs.BIO) category as it deals with the measurement of peripheral blood oxygen saturation, which is a vital measure in healthcare. 

The Signal Processing (cs.SI) category is also likely as the paper discusses the algorithms used for Sp02 sensing and proposes an alternative approach for reliable Sp02 sensing. 

The Operations Research (cs.OH) category is a possibility as the paper discusses the effect of sensor placement and skin tone on measurement error, which could be considered as optimization problems. 

Finally, the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category is a possibility as the paper discusses the potential of enabling oxygen saturation monitoring on wearable devices, which could open up new avenues of research in the field of networked health monitoring.
